{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015huCK2xbjsP4GDW1fm9kRn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The service exists but has NO Endpoints. This is because the pods aren't passing the readiness check. For headless services, the pods must be Ready for their IPs to appear in Endpoints. \n\nWait, actually for headless services with `clusterIP: None`, Kubernetes creates DNS entries based on the pods' IP addresses even when the pods aren't ready, IF the service has `publishNotReadyAddresses: true`. But by default, only ready pods get DNS entries.\n\nSo the issue is:\n1. Pods are running but NOT ready (readiness probe failing)\n2. Without ready pods, there are no endpoints and DNS fails\n3. Elasticsearch can't discover other nodes via DNS, so it can't form a cluster\n4. Without forming a cluster, the pods never become ready\n\nIt's a deadlock—the pods need to find each other to become ready, but they can't find each other until they're ready. The fix is adding `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` to the headless service, which tells Kubernetes to create DNS entries for all pods regardless of readiness status. I'll update the service definition with this flag.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":587,"cache_read_input_tokens":49420,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":587},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"04b80efa-7cc4-4368-9677-082eed58964b","uuid":"95e5d818-0d21-485d-84c3-8f1cd0ac5810","request_id":"req_011CcLw1b3wQG9YZ6upR1q9c"}
