{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013dp9BgoZWGagj4eR19vkXz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"DNS resolution IS working from within the ES pod. The `getent hosts es-cluster-1.es-cluster` resolves correctly. And `es-cluster.elasticsearch` resolves to all 3 pod IPs.\n\nSo the issue is that ES is using the full FQDN for DNS resolution via Java, and Java might be caching old DNS failures. ES should eventually discover the other nodes...\n\nActually wait - the `curl-test` pod couldn't resolve `es-cluster-0.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` but the ES pod can. Let me understand why this is different.\n\nLooking at the resolv.conf from the ES pod:\nThe search domains include `elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, which allows the short name `es-cluster-0.es-cluster` to resolve properly. But the curl-test pod is getting NXDOMAIN when trying the full FQDN, which is strange since both pods are in the same namespace and should have identical DNS configuration.\n\nI'm wondering if there's a timing issue here—the curl-test query happened before `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` was applied, while the ES pod test came after. Let me retry the full FQDN from curl-test to see if it works now. The Java error about `es-cluster-2.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` suggests this might be a DNS caching problem in the Java runtime.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":302,"cache_read_input_tokens":52243,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":302},"output_tokens":32,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"04b80efa-7cc4-4368-9677-082eed58964b","uuid":"e6c00203-45b3-4122-9d6f-f3a1e9ab4e17","request_id":"req_011CcLw48kUrsGnhMSRyYCFE"}
